# Random Choices
# This section explains how to use the random module.

# We already used the random module earlier in the course.

# For example, we used randint() in the Magic 8 Ball program
# to generate a random number.

# The random module actually contains many methods (around 22).

# Example showing how the choices() method works.

import random  # Import the random module so we can use its functions

dice = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]  # Create a list representing the sides of a dice

print(random.choices(dice))  # Randomly select one value from the list

# Explanation:
# The import keyword allows us to access a module.

# choices() randomly selects an item from a list.

# By default choices() returns one item in a list.

# We can also select multiple items using the parameter k.

import random  # Import the module again (if not already imported)

dice = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]  # List of dice values

print(random.choices(dice, k=3))  # Randomly select 3 values from the list

# The result will be a list containing three randomly chosen numbers.

# Each time the program runs, the result may be different.

# Important note:
# The k parameter only controls the number of items returned.
# The same value may appear more than once in the list.

